caption: It’s a nice Japanese/Asian restaurant. Place was quite and comfy on Thursday night and we enjoyed attentive and unobtrusive service. The interior is minimalistic, yet you feel the quality of the materials and effort being made. Combined with the lounge music and  light food - it’s the right place to enjoy the conversation and company. Rolls were not the best I had before, but it a taste thing...

We order from Shine often and the people are very friendly. It is a good price point for good sushi. I wouldn’t say it’s the best sushi in the area, but for a casual night when I’m craving sushi, this is our neighborhood go-to. We dine in on the patio and also order take out often.
Great price for the quality you get - there's some really creative rolls here. Definitely worth a try!

The Flaming Maki was my favorite followed by the Ichiban roll and lastly the Yuzu Roll which was still great with the lemon zest,  I just don't love spicy tuna. The food was really the reason for a 3 star rating. It was subpar. We used to go to Rise at least once a week. We loved their sushi rolls, their appetizers were phenomenal! Sadly,  with thr merge of Rise and Shine, we definitely did not feel that Shine is anything like Rise. Shine claims to have the same menu as Rise, however when we placed our exact order from Rise at Shine (we dined in, fyi) everything was different. The shrimp appetizer we always got at Rise was not at all the way we have had it for the past 10 yrs. Presentation was bad, the actual dish itself, DID NOT resemble Rise's appetizer. Such a disappointment.  The sushi rolls Rise had also fell flat at Shine. They did not resemble the Rise signature rolls at all! Ugh...sad to say but we will not be returning to Shine. Rise, R.I.P. wish they would have kept Rise and shut down Shine instead. The staff and the service was great, so at least they have that going for them. Their dividers for COVID are cheap and the plastic wall kept flying into our table, which was super annoying. Grrrr...

We had a 530 reservation and while it was quiet when we arrived, the place quickly filled up. It is family friendly but also great for date night. We loved the mochi balls for dessert. My family and I have been going to Shine for ~10 years. It’s been our go-to sushi restaurant all this time and we have loved it. However, the level of service my family and I received during dinner tonight was one of the worst  restaurant experiences I’ve had. It started with the hostess who was not the kindest. Then, about an hour and 15 minutes after we sat down the waitress told us they needed us to leave because they had reservations, but we also had reservations and weren’t yet finished with our meal. She proceeded to give us strong attitude and remind us multiple times that others were waiting, which was not our fault. They should have better planned their reservations. Truly disappointing considering how often we’ve frequented the restaurant and the number of people we’ve introduced to the restaurant.

Shine has quickly become my favorite go-to restaurant in Lincoln Park.  Firstly, the owner and all staff welcome you with a smile, and genuinely appreciate you choosing to dine there.  Secondly, the food is phenomenal!  Each of their dishes is unique, and the food (esp. veggies) are all so fresh!  And such kind and informative wait staff...  Finally, you are always thanked for coming on your way out - genuine appreciation and assurance that you enjoyed your meal and experience.  And that's why I keep going back!!

Great service and delicious food. This is a really good place to take a date.  They are also part of the Spring Network, so that's always handy.

The service is excellent -- friendly and careful to get the order just right.   I had a green curry with tofu and mango bubble tea.  The bubble tea was tangy and flavorful from top to bottom (some places can be watery toward the bottom).  The curry had the right amount of heat -- I don't mind that it came from jalapeno rather than Thai chili.  It had a rich flavor, and wasn't overly liquid.  The veggies were still "alive" tasting, and the Japanese eggplant in it is really good.  There is also a LOT of food there -- two meals for moderate eaters, 1 for big eaters.  Another plus is that they have good brown rice as an option at no extra charge.  I heard a few other tables talk about how they loved the sushi.  I can't comment on it myself, but I take it as a good sign that they have consistently good staff in the kitchen.  The only reason I didn't give it 5 stars is that they had the doors open to the sidewalk dining area, so the 90+ degree heat and humidity came inside -- ick.  Plus, I only tried the one dish.  I'll definitely go back to try the Singapore noodles, and if they are just as good, I'll bump my rating up to 5 stars.  One thing for sure, it is a lot better than most of the Thai places I've been to, which are kind of stale smelling and/or have bland, greasy curry drowning in coconut milk.  Oh, another plus... the place is clean, including the restroom -- a welcome change from a lot of the places.

This is a neighborhood sushi place.  It's a great place for a date-night with good cocktails, beer, and slightly-if-not-in-line-with-the-zip-code-overpriced sushi.  The rolls are well put together, and the service is decent.

Two things:  Akuma Maki  & Flaming Maki  You're welcome.  Also, Lychee martinis are to die for.
